TY  - JOUR
T1  - Designs for Environmental Scanning Systems: Tests of a Contingency Theory
AU  - Yasai-Ardekani, Masoud
AU  - Nystrom, Paul C.
Y1  - 1996/02/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.42.2.187
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.42.2.187
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 187
EP  - 204
VL  - 42
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This study compared the relationships between organizational context and the designs of environmental scanning systems for organizational with effective and ineffective scanning systems. The study analyzed data from over 100 North American business organizations. Results indicate that organizations with effective scanning systems tend to align their scanning designs with the requirements of their context. On the other hand, the results show that organizations with ineffective scanning systems typically fail to exhibit the requisite level of alignment between contexts and scanning design.
AB  - This study compared the relationships between organizational context and the designs of environmental scanning systems for organizational with effective and ineffective scanning systems. The study analyzed data from over 100 North American business organizations. Results indicate that organizations with effective scanning systems tend to align their scanning designs with the requirements of their context. On the other hand, the results show that organizations with ineffective scanning systems typically fail to exhibit the requisite level of alignment between contexts and scanning design.
